04842nam a2200685Ia 9781787441699DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182018xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874416997 a10.1515/97817874416992doi  a(DE-B1597)677147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPT411 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a830.9/382972231 aTwist, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMystical Islam and Cosmopolitanism in Contemporary German Literature :bOpenness to Alterity /cJoseph Twist.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2018] 1bCamden House, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v18500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Spirituality, Cosmopolitanism, and Muslim German Writers -- t1: Between Heaven and Earth, and Self and Other: Zafer Şenocak’s Übergang -- t2: Poetry, Prayer, and Apostasy: SAID’s Psalmen -- t3: Romantic Religion and Counter-Enlightenment Cosmopolitanism: Feridun Zaimoglu’s Liebesbrand -- t4: Between Pleasure and Terror: The Divine in Navid Kermani’s Fiction -- tConclusion: Intellectual, Spiritual, and Cultural Renewal -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHighlights the spirituality and cosmopolitanism of four contemporary German Muslim writers, showing that they undermine the "clash-of-civilizations" narrative and open up space for new ways of coexisting.At a time when the place of Muslims in German society is being disputed, this book explores how four contemporary German writers of Muslim backgrounds - Zafer Senocak, SAID, Feridun Zaimoglu, and Navid Kermani - point beyond identity politics and suggest new ways of thinking about religion and community. Twist highlights both the spirituality and the cosmopolitanism of these authors, bringing their thought into dialogue with the work of Jean-Luc Nancy.Nancy is critical of communities based on a single guiding principle (be it God or Reason) and thus involving a universalizing core that leads to conflicts between identity groups. He proposes alternative notions of both religious faith (a postmonotheistic version with elements of mysticism) and community (spontaneous communities requiring no shared identity). Twist relates these arguments to post-9/11 debates over cosmopolitanism and religion, illuminating how the writers under study draw upon mystical Islam's deconstructive potential, finding divine insight in love, sex, music, pain, and beauty. Such a worldly and affective spirituality dispels associations between Islam and sexual conservatism while rejecting monotheistic ideology. Thus, unlike the homogenizing drive of universalist cosmopolitanism, these writers' nonfoundational conceptualizations undermine the twenty-first century's "clash-of-civilizations" narrative and open up space for new ways of coexisting. JOSEPH TWIST is Fixed-term Lecturer in German at University College Dublin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthors, Araby21st century. 0aAuthors, Germany21st century. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismy21st century. 4aGerman Literature. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAlterity.  aCosmopolitanism.  aErotic relationships.  aGerman Muslim writers.  aIntersubjective.  aIslam.  aJean-Luc Nancy.  aMystic.  aReligion.  aSpirituality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787441699?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787441699423Coveruhtt